<paragraph blockId="19.[125,220,650,674]" box="[125,220,650,674]" pageId="19" pageNumber="3968">
<emphasis box="[125,220,650,674]" italics="true" pageId="19" pageNumber="3968">Remarks</emphasis>
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="19.[125,1172,699,819]" pageId="19" pageNumber="3968">
This species resembles 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Okada" authorityYear="1977" box="[394,501,699,723]" class="Insecta" family="Drosophilidae" genus="Amiota" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diptera" pageId="19" pageNumber="3968" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="cardua">
<emphasis box="[394,501,699,723]" italics="true" pageId="19" pageNumber="3968">P. cardua</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
in having the anepisternum lacking setulae, and the shape of the paramere and gonopod, but can be distinguished from the latter species by the arista and the vertical processes of the gonopod (
<taxonomicName authorityName="Okada" authorityYear="1977" box="[631,739,763,787]" class="Insecta" family="Drosophilidae" genus="Amiota" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diptera" pageId="19" pageNumber="3968" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="cardua">
<emphasis box="[631,739,763,787]" italics="true" pageId="19" pageNumber="3968">P. cardua</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
has only one short ventral branch in the arista; vertical process of gonopod depressed and unsclerotized medially).
</paragraph>
